e 9th 1785, in the 50th year of his age.'"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Led Connecticut's 9th Regiment of Foot as Lt.","body":"Stephen Saint John rose to Lieutenant Colonel in command of the 9th Regiment of Foot, Guard of the State of Connecticut — a rank inscribed on his tombstone in East Norwalk Historical Cemetery. His family's marriage alliances connected two of Norwalk's most prominent dynasties: the Saint Johns married into the Fitches across two consecutive generations."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"He sent no substitute; his brother did","body":"A Connecticut selectman and Revolutionary officer, he led the colony’s 9th Regiment of Foot. When the war came, an enslaved man named Dover was sent to fight in the Continental Army in place of his brother — while his own household still held two people, Peter and Phyllis, at his death."}],"career":[{"role":"Selectman","organization":"Norwalk, Connecticut","notes":"1763-1784"},{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut House","notes":"1778-1785"},{"role":"Lt. Colonel","organization":"9th Connecticut Regiment"}],"slug":"stephen-st-john-1736"},"X00216":{"id":"X00216","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"St. John Genealogy (Alexander, 1907)","url":"https://ia601308.us.archive.org/2/items/stjohngenealogyd00lcalex/stjohngenealogyd00lcalex.pdf"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00479","date_year":1757,"date_month":12,"date_day":9,"children_ids":["H01238","H01239","H01237","H01240","H01236"]}],"parents":{"father_name":"Hon. Samuel Fitch","mother_name":"Susannah Fitch","father_research_notes":"Per St. John Genealogy (Alexander 1907), entry 141: 'the dau. of Hon. Samuel and Susa